summary: When I see people comparing the scene in Winter Soldier where Steve puts his shield away to fight Batroc, to the scene in...
body:
When I see people comparing the scene in Winter Soldier where Steve puts his shield away to fight Batroc, to the scene in Captain Marvel where she just blasts Yon-Rogg instead of fighting him… well, beyond the fact that they’re different characters in vastly different circumstances, it’s not an accurate comparison powers-wise either.

Captain America is still technically human, but he is borderline superhuman. He is as strong, fast, agile, etc as a human can possibly be. Putting his shield away doesn’t negate any of that. The shield is only as effective as it is with him because of his reflexes and strength. Yeah, it’s vibranium but he’s able to throw and catch it and use it the way he does because of his enhanced abilities. Steve by himself fighting against any regular human without any advanced tech isn’t really a fair fight regardless of whether he has his shield or not. He’s still utilizing his superior abilities after he puts the shield away.

Carol doesn’t have a shield to put away, but her powers are every bit as much a part of her as Steve’s enhanced abilities are. So of course she uses them in a fight. Steve didn’t really step down to Batroc’s level when he put the shield away, he was just being a smartass about Batroc’s comment by doing so. Carol’s not gonna come down to Yon-Rogg’s level (she can’t, really… she’s just way more powerful than him anyway lol) because he’s spent years telling her she wasn’t good enough without what he and the Kree gave her when really they were just holding her back. He expects her to be thankful and want his approval but she doesn’t need it and she knows what a toxic manipulator he is. It’s like he’s an ant that keeps stinging someone’s foot but it doesn’t realize the foot can just squash it lol. Or maybe like dealing with a bully on the Internet. You don’t have anything to prove to them, so just photon blast them/block them.
